      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "By the five-year mark, you'll be seeing a good chunk of your payment go toward the principal, though the interest still makes a significant dent. Much more so by year twenty-five, the principal portion will be noticeably larger, because that's when the interest accrual starts to really shrink. Think of it like a slow, steady tide, but the tide is mostly pulling the principal in by the end.\n\nHere’s the general idea, though I can't pull up your specific Wells Fargo statement for you—that's where the real magic happens, and you'll need to look at the amortization schedule they provide. But I can tell you the *pattern*, which is what matters most, even if it's just a rough sketch.\n\nFor a 30-year fixed at 6.5%, your initial payment is set. In the early years, say year five, a large portion of that payment is just servicing the interest on the big, looming debt. When you hit year twenty-five, the interest calculation is based on a much smaller remaining balance, so the principal portion of your payment gets a bigger slice of the pie. It’s like a slow-moving, very",
