    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but can you be a bit more specific? like if my monthly payment is $2000, roughly what percentage of that is interest in year 5 versus year 25? i just want to get a better feel for how much of my money is basically just being eaten up by the interest component early on.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A $2000 payment on a 6.5% loan, you're looking at a good chunk of that payment being eaten by interest early on. In the early years, like year five, you'll likely find that the interest component is still dominating, perhaps around 70% to 75% of your total payment. By year twenty-five, that shifts dramatically; the interest portion will drop significantly, maybe down to 35% to 40% of your payment.\n\nThis shift is the key, because it shows how the interest is a real, persistent, and often greedy thing when you first start paying down the debt. It's like a slow-moving, very sticky piece of cheese that clings to the principal until you start chipping away at it.\n\nThink of it this way: in year five, you're mostly feeding the interest monster. By year twenty-five, you're finally starting to starve that monster by attacking the principal directly. If you're worried about the interest eating you alive, that early period is when you need to be most vigilant.\n\n*A little side note: I was just thinking about a little spider-like creature I saw in",
      "source": "target",
